nt is the critically acclaimed song writing of Jenny Lester, Bob Hamilton and Mark Thibeault, Ross Nickerson &amp; Nadine Landry. We are pleased to announce that touring with Hungry Hill is the internationally acclaimed banjo player Ross Nickerson from Baltimore. Please see <a href=\"http://www.bangoteacher.com/\">www.banjoteacher.com</a> for an amazing and complete read. Though the band misses Matt King since his move to the Solomon Islands, we proudly introduce Nadine Landry from Whitehorse on acoustic bass fiddle and heart-melting vocals. <br />\r\n<a id=\"ctl00_Main_ctl00_UserBasicInformation1_hlDefaultImage\" href=\"http://viewmorepics.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=user.viewAlbums&amp;friendID=127546375\"><em><img style=\"border-width: 0px\" src=\"http://a18.ac-images.myspacecdn.com/images01/68/m_08de5140bbfc719977bc30127efb5f89.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"170\" height=\"170\" /></em></a><br />\r\n<br />\r\nBased out of Whitehorse, Yukon Territory, Canada. \r\n</p>\r\n',1,'Nadine Landry - Bass<br />\r\nJenny Lester - Fiddle / Guitar<br />\r\nMark Thibeault - Rayco Resophinc Guitar / Guitar<br />\r\nRoss Nickerson - Banjo<br />\r\nBob Hamilton&nbsp; - Mandolin<br />\r\n<a id=\"ctl00_cpMain_UserViewPictureControl_ImageListings1_dlImageList_ctl00_hypImage\" href=\"http://viewmorepics.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=viewImage&amp;friendID=127546375&amp;albumID=0&amp;imageID=1577198\" title=\"Hungry Hill - All Photos - Photo 1 of 18\" class=\"photo_image\"><img style=\"border-width: 0px\" src=\"http://b9.ac-images.myspacecdn.com/01531/99/02/1531442099_m.jpg\" alt=\"\" title=\"Hungry Hill - All Photos - Photo 1 of 18\" width=\"170\" height=\"164\" /></a> \r\n',0,''),(2448,1000231,'GuyWhoRecords',1,66,'http://GuyWhoRecords.com','','','Guy Who Does not have time yet to do this Bio.\r\n',0,'',0,''),(2449,1000234,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','',1,'',0,''),(2450,1000238,'Lil JinxXx',4,24,'http://myspace.com/liljinxxxmuzik','','(520) 508-6268','',0,'',0,''),(2451,1000239,'Intuitive music orchestra',106,NULL,'http://www.ianbederman.com','23/31 Malaya Pionerskaya str., apt. 71, Moscow, Russia','','&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<div><br /></div>',1,'<span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: bold\">Ian Bederman</span><div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: bold\">John Kukaryamba</span></div><div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: bold\">Vladimir Nelinov</span></div><div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: bold\">Andrey Bayramov</span></div><div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: bold\">Ariadna Karyagina</span></div>',0,''),(2452,1000240,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','',1,'',0,''),(2453,1000241,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','',1,'',0,''),(2454,1000242,'glen andrews lazy 6',11,93,'http://mothershipentertainment.com','','','In New Orleans, the city that gave the world jazz, a young trombone player and vocalist is proudly taking that style of music into the 21st Century. \r\n<p>\r\nGlenn David Andrews, 23, articulates his city&rsquo;s deep musical heritage through his performing better than anyone his age. He has one foot planted in the more contemporary, funky sounds that define today&rsquo;s New Orleans brass band scene; meanwhile, Andrews shows his elders the respect he believes they deserve, as his other foot rests firmly in the music&rsquo;s time-honored traditions. &ldquo;Traditional jazz, the way it was played 100 years ago, is dying out with my generation,&rdquo; Andrews says. &ldquo;And I&rsquo;m not about to let that happen.&rdquo; By combining the old with the new, Andrews has created a unique sound, one that is currently captivating New Orleans music fans. \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nAndrews certainly possesses the pedigree to carry this illustrious New Orleans musical flame. Growing up in the historic Treme section of the city, one of the first black neighborhoods in America, Andrews was immersed in the thick of New Orleans culture from the get go. Musical legends like Earl Palmer, James Black and George Lewis once walked his neighborhood&rsquo;s streets and played in its clubs, as do some of today&rsquo;s young lions, such as Nicholas Payton, Kermit Ruffins and Shannon Powell. \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nKnown by locals as the &ldquo;Sixth Ward,&rdquo; the Treme still hosts &ldquo;Second Line&rdquo; parades on most Sundays, with brass bands and dancers rambling through its bars and streets. These unique, celebratory occasions have been taking place in this neighborhood for at least a century. Into this scene came Glenn David Andrews, eager to soak it all in. &ldquo;I love it,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;I wouldn&rsquo;t want to grow up anywhere else.&rdquo; \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nChances are that whatever band is leading one of these parades (the ReBirth, Li&rsquo;l Rascals or the Newbirth Brass Band), a few of its members will likely share the same last name: Andrews. This family is currently producing highly talented young musicians at an astonishing rate. Glen David&rsquo;s first cousins, James and Troy &ldquo;Trombone Shorty&rdquo; Andrews, are local favorites; so are Glen and Revert &ldquo;Peanut&rdquo; Andrews, who both hold court with the ReBirth Brass Band. Since he began playing his instrument at age 13, Glen David has performed with almost every brass band in the city. His boisterous voice and warm trombone style are fixtures on the streets, and he adds his own flavor to whatever band he is supporting that day and always makes it sound better. Now he is stepping out on his own, ready to take New Orleans music up from the streets and bring it to the rest of the world. \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nHis ability to add new songs to the brass band repertoire is matchless for a performer so young. Songs like &ldquo;Knock with Me, Rock with Me&rdquo; and &ldquo;Show Me How You Do That Dance&rdquo; are not only street favorites, but have also received sizeable commercial radio airplay, an honor that has eluded brass band music since the ReBirth Brass Band recorded its signature tune, &ldquo;Do Whatcha Wanna,&rdquo; almost 20 years ago. &ldquo;I am writing all the time, and my lyrics just come out of me,&rdquo; Andrews explains. &ldquo;And that&rsquo;s the way it should be, because this is heart and soul music.&rdquo; \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nAndrews is becoming a full-blown star in New Orleans, and his powerful vocals and soulful trombone playing recently drew attention at the Louis Armstrong &ldquo;Satchmo Summer Festival&rdquo; as well as on the stage of the local music shrine, Tipitina&rsquo;s. &ldquo;People are starting to take notice,&rdquo; Andrews observes. &ldquo;I know how to take charge of a stage.&rdquo; One minute he&rsquo;ll have you feeling the solemn power of an old time spiritual from the 19 th century, and the next you&rsquo;ll be jumping higher in the air than you ever thought possible while chanting at the top of your lungs. This seamless mixing of styles sets Glen David Andrews apart from his contemporaries. Through his music, he brings musical history to life, while also creating a new sound that is all his. \r\n</p>\r\n',1,'',0,''),(2455,1000244,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','',1,'',0,''),(2456,1000247,'Suicidal Poets',1,71,'http://www.myspace.com/suicidalpoets','62 Avenue F, Lodi NJ 07644','201-674-6247','<font color=\"#800000\">CHECK OUT OUR FEATURE ON THE NBT PODCAST...NextBigThing!!!<br />\r\nHear 2 tracks from the band, plus intros &amp; insights from Michelle!<br />\r\nGo to:<br />\r\nhttp://nextbigthing.libsyn.com<br />\r\n<br />\r\nthen, VOTE for the Podcast at &#39;Podcast Alley&#39;, and help to keep the show rated in the Top 10 Podcasts, at:<br />\r\nhttp://www.podcastalley.com/podcast details.php?pod id=2966<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTHANKS!!!<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSuicidal Poets are Notorious for their Poetic Lyrics and Musical Originality. They are a crossover between Folk, Rock, Pop, Alternative. The Suicidal Poets launched onto the Internet music scene April 1999 and that was like Opening a Wind